>     There's a word "serendipity" which applies to this.  

"serendipity" is an interesting word. I first heard of it here:

http://www.perl.com/pub/a/2004/09/09/lightning.html

According to 
http://www.m-w.com/cgi-bin/dictionary?book=Dictionary&va=serendipity it comes 
from the Persian Fairy Tale "The Three Princes of Serendip". I believe I've 
seen it on the Hallmark channel.

>     I was very struck 
> by your bringing up Albert Einstein, because at the time I was reading a
> book that was teaching me much about him that I wasn't aware of before (the
> title of the book is "Einstein's Clocks and Poincare's Maps").   And I was
> much reminded of you.  Einstein was at very young age, about 16 or so, when
> he first started developing an interest in "the nature of the universe".
> And at a very young age, he started becoming skeptical of the then
> prevailing theories.  About the time he had earned his first
> (undergraduate) degree, he started writing letters to the leading
> physicists of the time. There's an existing letter he wrote to his
> girlfriend telling about one such letter in which he describes how he
> sharply challenges some of the man's ideas, and he also says "Of course I
> told him I didn't have a job." 

Interesting.

> And, if you can take heart from this, 
> Einstein had a very difficult time finding a job when he was first out of
> university.  He wanted to teach, but no institution would hire him. 

Did he went from one institution to the other, and each one had its own 
reasons for not hiring him? Or was it because of some reputation he got?

> I'm 
> sure you're aware that he went to work for the Swiss Patent Office. 

Yes, I know.

> Another thing I learned was that that was not as "menial" a job as one
> might imagine (at least in the US these days, the job of patent examiner
> carries virtually no prestige at all). The Swiss Patent Office in
> Einstein's time was a prestigious institution, and the examiners generally
> dealt with inventors very much on their own terms.
>

Interesting.

